[h1]The Good[/h1]
+[b]Music[/b]. Needless to say, developed in mind as a spiritual successor to Guilty Gear and by the same group of talents, BlazBlue has no right to not to have awesome music. BBCPEX opening song 'Blue Desire' is still one of my all-time favorite (here in case you wanna check it yourself: [url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-oKoi8JkvCE]Blue Desire[/url]).
+[b]Sound[/b]. Sound effects are improved compared with its predecessors. However, there are still some scenarios with cramped sounds, depending on which move is being used or the various status(being hit, on guard, etc) your character is in. I'd say Persona 4 Arena has overall better sound effects than this.
+[b]Voice[/b]. That's a fat plus here. These VA are all A-listers across Japan. If you are an anime guy (a weeb, that is), you'll definitely find yourself enjoying these familiar voices in the game.
+[b]Mechanism[/b]. It's a 4-button 2D anime fighter game, which some of us would call it '喧哗流‘ due to its fast pace and combo-heavy gameplay. Some of the westerners would call it "air-dasher" because of its smooth in-air maneuver: you can perform an air dash(*that isn't as sluggish as in S-hite-rive) and double jump(except for some characters, they have their own movement choice). To me the movement/mobility is always the kernel or essence of a fighting game. The representation of this game is definitely complicated yet pleasant. For example, you have 3 ways of neutral tech, 4 types of guard, etc. With so many options at your disposal, it'll take sometime to learn and use it in actual matches, but 4REED∅M is where all the fun lies, right? (*unlike that dumbass S-hite-rive, everything feels so restricted lmao) If you are a traditional type of fighting game player, you probably are not gonna like it. A dull person would always prefer boring games, that's perfectly fine by me, it's your loss.
+[b]Combat[/b]. Well that's where the gem is. This game has one of the most interesting fighting system. Not only there is a Distinct 'D-Drive' system and ’Overdrive‘ mode that gives unique boost for each characters(kinda works like the Vorpal state in Under Night), the moveset is also cleverly designed to match their fighting style as well as grants the flexibility to express your own playstyle (*unlike the clownish S-hite-rive with its pathetic skill ceiling that forces every high-level match a replica). This battle system as the epitome of the Blazblue franchise, has been through 10+ years of iterations. It will unleash its full potential to create the most breathtaking moments in duals between every 2 different characters, in the right hands (*definitely not in the hands of S-hite-rive degenerates lol)

[h1]The 'Neutral'[/h1]
~[b]Story[/b]. Could be one of the biggest reasons for some people to buy this game, especially if you like gal-game or those otaku things(lots of fan service). This is the last chapter of Ragna the protagonist's story, so if you want to experience the whole thing, I'd recommend you to start from the <Blazblue Continuum Shift Extend> which is the 2nd entry. Also, notice that this game only concludes the ending for ‘Ragna', but does not necessarily mean the end for Blazblue World. [strike]In fact, ASW is publishing a mobile game focus on the magic school daily life of the 'Six Heroes' early next year.[/strike] Fun fact: the mobile game was released 3 years later and couldn't manage to survive the first entire year lol.
Story itself is worth 6-7 hours reading(each for BBCSEX, BBCPEX and BBCF which is this one), along with several novels as prequel(around 10 books or so), an anime(terrible), a manga(story about Mai? I think) and other stuff, for lore monsters lol.
 ~[b]Characters[/b]. I'd say they are more on the dripless side if set side by side with Guilty Gear. But there are still some interesting characters design details and references to other famous titles, such as Fullmetal Alchemist. Every character has been put effort in by the developers, undeniably. The game comes with a very decent illustration book(pdf format) which you can find in your steam folder. 

[h1]The Not So Good[/h1]
-[b]Terrible graphic[/b]. The series is based on hardware over a decade ago, all the sources(character image, animation, etc) are in 768p resolution. A bunch of graphic options have been added to this newest installment, though, the anti aliasing won't work properly and even if these settings are all cranked up, graphic still looks blurry as Biden's pants. Not to mention that the Vsync will always be forced on by the game in all resolution other than 1080p, even you turn it off. 
-LOL the [b]UI[/b] deteriorates since the very beginning of the series. And this entry is at its doom's valley. But, be that as it may, still 10 times better than S-hite-rive's no-soul UI that looks like from a cheap card gacha game.
-[b]Optimization[/b]. I have a RTX 2080ti so I don't really know what is going on here, but from the previous titles in this game and most of the community comments here, it was not so well optimized at release. However, with its recent rollback code update,  the file size has also been dramatically reduced, surprise! 
-[b]Netcode[/b]. [strike]The community is not very active on PC. And the connection suffers from lags which could be annoying for a 60fps fighting title.[/strike] Rollback our lord and savior. Not only rollbacks alleviates input delay, allows connections between further geological places, more importantly, it also brings back an active player base, a resurgence of the game's lifespan. Now, about GGXrd...
-[b]Beginner unfriendly[/b]. I played 100+ hours and am still on the barely above noob level. The best way to deal with this and have a feeling of progression is to find a good friend at about the same skill level, practice and git gud together. However, a game like BBCF that requires frequently button pressing only means the execution requirement is high. It's not necessarily 'mashy' as some idiots claimed. It's not the game 'mashy', it's your brain, loser. As a code of conduct in almost every fighting game, the first thing is always [u]play the tutorial mode, learn the system[/u]. The tutorial is well structured and detailed, help you get into the game more efficiently. Learn the combo, defense and offense, overall gameplan of your character through character primer, discord, dustloop wiki, the fun just begins and only gets better from here :-)

